{
  "research_summary": [
    "Both Sir Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz are independently credited with inventing calculus in the late 17th century.",
    "Newton began developing his form of calculus, which he called 'fluxions and fluents,' in the mid-1660s, but published his comprehensive work much later.",
    "Leibniz started developing his version of calculus in the 1670s, publishing his first papers on differential calculus in 1684 and integral calculus in 1686.",
    "A bitter priority dispute erupted between the two mathematicians and their followers, fueled by accusations of plagiarism, particularly after Newton's supporters claimed Leibniz had seen Newton's unpublished work.",
    "Leibniz's notation (e.g., dy/dx for derivatives and the elongated S for integrals) proved more flexible and is the system predominantly used today.",
    "Modern historical consensus generally acknowledges that both Newton and Leibniz independently invented calculus, arriving at similar results through different approaches and with distinct notations."
  ]
}
